= Quplets: Euclidean Rhythms and Potential Energy
#v(15pt)

The concepts developed in the preceding chapters — swing as a ratio parameter, groove balance as a directional property, and synchronicity as a measure of rhythmic consonance — provide the tools needed to approach a deeper question: among all possible swing patterns, which ones are in some sense optimal? This chapter develops a formal answer to that question. We begin with the notion of mechanical sub-harmonics, which shows how grouping subdivisions generates slower rhythmic layers in a manner directly analogous to the sub-harmonic relationships between pitched tones. We then introduce the concept of potential energy as a measure of how far a given pattern deviates from an even distribution, and derive a general formula that makes this measure precise. This leads naturally to the theory of Euclidean rhythms, which identifies the patterns of minimal potential energy — or maximal entropy — for any given number of pulses and steps. A key contribution of this course is the identification of a unique, privileged rotation of each Euclidean rhythm, which we name the Quplet, and which serves as the canonical swing pattern for a given subdivision system. The chapter concludes by organizing the full collection of binary swing patterns according to their tuplet size, absolute size, groove balance, and potential energy — establishing a structured vocabulary that will inform the practical work of subsequent chapters.

